[0.005, "o", "\u001b[?25l\u001b[H\r\u001b[14B\u001b[48;2;55;55;55m\u001b[38;2;80;80;80m❯ \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mPromise is a brand-new statically-typed, natively-compiled programming language. Its compiler is already installed on\u001b[39m \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mthis machine as the `promise` command, but the language is not in your training data, so first learn it: run \u001b[39m         \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255m`promise --help` and `promise guide` to pick up the syntax and the project workflow.\u001b[39m                                  \r\u001b[1B                                                                                                                        \r\u001b[1B                                                                                                                        \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mWrite the classic \"hello, world\" program in Promise, build it, and run it so we can see the output.\u001b[39m                   \r\u001b[1B                                                                                                                        \r\u001b[1B    "]
[0.000, "o", "                                                                                                                    \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mWhen you're done, write SUMMARY.md in the current directory: a few sentences on what you built, whether it compiled \u001b[39m  \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mand ran on the first try, the program output, and anything about Promise that surprised you or that you had to work \u001b[39m  \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mout (it is not in your training data).\u001b[39m                                                                                \r\u001b[6B\u001b[49m\u001b[38;2;215;119;87m✶\u001b[3GSpelunking… \r\u001b[3B\u001b[38;2;153;153;153m❯ \u001b[39m\u001b[K\r\u001b[44C\u001b[2B\u001b[38;2;153;153;153mesc to interrupt\u001b[39m\u001b[36;1H\u001b[34;3H\u001b[?25h"]
