[0.000, "o", "ge. Its compiler is already installed on\u001b[39m \r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;255;255;255mthis machine\u001b[16Gas the `promise` command, but \u001b[47Ghe \u001b[51Ganguage is\u001b[62Gnot in your\u001b[74Gtraining da\u001b[86Ga, so first le\u001b[101Grn it:\u001b[108Grun \u001b[39m        \r\u001b[2C\u001b[1B\u001b[38;2;255;255;255m`promise --help` and `promise\u001b[33Gguide` to pick up the syntax\u001b[62Gand\u001b[66Gthe project workflow.\u001b[39m                         \r\u001b[2C\u001b[1B                                                                                    \r\u001b[2C\u001b[2B\u001b[38;2;255;255;255mWrite the classic \"hello, world\" program in Promise, build it, and run it so we can see the output.\r\u001b[2C\u001b[1B\u001b[39m                                                                                                   \r\u001b[2C\u001b[2B\u001b[38;2;255;255;255mWhen you're done, write SUMMARY.md in the current directory: a few sentences on what you built, whether it compiled \r\u001b[2C\u001b[1Band ran on the first \u001b[25Gry, the program\u001b[41Goutput, a\u001b[51Gd\u001b[53Ganything about Promis\u001b[75G that surprised yo\u001b[94G or that you\u001b[107Ghad to work\r\u001b[2C\u001b[1Bout"]
